# Assembly Language Rules

## Intent
Reserve pure assembly for platform-specific kernels, intimately performance-sensitive loops, or bootstrapping helpers when the higher-level language cannot express the necessary ABI. Favor readable comments and labeled sections so Cursor tours stay approachable.

## Setup & Toolchain
- Use NASM or `yasm` with `-f elf64` (Linux), `-f macho64` (macOS), or `-f win64` (Windows). Keep the selected format noted here for future replication.
- Assemble with the same linker flags used by the corresponding C/C++ project:
  ```sh
  nasm -f elf64 src/boot.asm -o build/boot.o
  gcc build/boot.o build/main.o -o bin/bootloader
  ```
- Provide a `linker.cmd` or `link.ld` sample and document where to place the generated object files.

## Structure & Rules
- Always define explicit sections (`section .data`, `section .text`) and align instructions to cache lines when hinting perf.
- Document calling conventions, preserved registers, and stack discipline in comments at the top of each `.asm` file.
- Export macros with descriptive names and keep macro-based loops short to avoid confusing Cursor's tour flow.

## Integration Notes
1. Call assembly stubs from C/C++ via `extern` declarations; keep prototypes in `include/asm.h`.
2. Wrap any inline assembly (`asm volatile("...")`) in helper functions so the tour can trace usage without parsing complex templates.
3. Share reusable jump tables, macros, or data blobs through `data.inc` files referenced from multiple languages.

## Validation & Replication
- Attach simple smoke tests (`tests/asm-smoke.sh`) that run the assembly snippets through the same toolchain as the rest of the project.
- Record the steps to duplicate this setup in `.repliaction/replication.mdc` so future instances maintain consistent assembler flags and file naming conventions.

